ğŸ”¹ Person (ABSTRACT CLASS)
Purpose:
Represents a generic human entity in the system.

Why abstract?
Because a Person alone doesnâ€™t make sense â€” only specific types like students.

Fields (Protected):
Field	    Type  	Description
id	        int	    Unique identifier
name    	String	Personâ€™s full name
Methods:
Method	Description
getRole()	Abstract â†’ implemented by subclasses
getId()	Returns ID
getName()	Returns name
public abstract String getRole();
ğŸ”¹ Student (CONCRETE CLASS)
Purpose:
Represents a student enrolled in the institute.

Inheritance:
Student extends Person

Fields:
Field	Type	Description
course	String	Course enrolled (Java, Spring, etc.)
Responsibilities:
Hold student data

Convert itself into a file-friendly format

@Override
public String toString() {
    return id + "," + name + "," + course;
}
âœ… OOP Concepts:
Inheritance, overriding, encapsulation

âœ… REPOSITORY LAYER (FILE MANAGEMENT MOVED HERE âœ…)
ğŸ”¹ StudentRepository (INTERFACE)
Purpose:
Defines WHAT operations are required
(does not care HOW data is stored).

Methods:
Method	Description
save(Student)	Persist student
findAll()	Load all students
void save(Student student) throws Exception;
List<Student> findAll() throws Exception;
ğŸ”¹ FileStudentRepository (IMPLEMENTATION)
Purpose:
Handles ALL FILE OPERATIONS related to students.

ğŸ“Œ File is stored as:

students.txt
ğŸ“Œ File format (CSV):

